The dataset provided for our group was Food data infection and the data was present in the xlsx format. Now, in order to import and read the data a package named readxl was installed. After reading the dataset, we decided to rename the column ‘Genus Species’ to ‘gspecies’. On checking the dimensions of the data, it was found to have 19,119 rows and 12 columns. Evaluating the variable types in the dataset has shown only 5 columns i.e Year, Month, Hospitalizations, Illnesses, and Deaths to be numeric and the rest were character. Among all the columns, Year, gspecies, Hospitalizations, Illnesses and Deaths were selected to be the important features for our study.

Tentative Objective: Genus Species and State influences food contamination that can lead to the highest number of deaths and Hospitalizations?

Groups: Year and Genus Species

Features: Deaths, Illnesses, Hospitalizations

Duplicating the dataframe

new_data<-data

Selecting the interested variables

req_variables = new_data %>%
  select('Year','gspecies','Deaths','Illnesses','Hospitalizations')

Analysis on the raw data quality i.e.,the Central Tendency Measures for all the features selected: Central tendency measures for the selected features were computed. Since the data has missing values, these values were omitted from the data. After the data cleaning process, the data had 10,444 rows and 5 columns.

#central tendency measures for the required columns
describe(req_variables)

#omitting the NA values
req_variables_copy<- req_variables %>%
  na.omit()

#Exploratory Data Analysis
#install.packages('ggplot2')
library(ggplot2)

A box plot for the numeric columns in the selected features i.e Hospitalizations, Illnesses and Deaths was computed. It was found that deaths were mostly distributed from 0-500 and no outliers were found. Illnesses were also distributed from 0-500 and no outliers were found. However, Hospitalizations were in the range of 0 - 1500, most concentrated in the range of 0-500 with few outliers in the range of 100-1500.

#1.Boxplots for the features
boxplot(req_variables_copy$Deaths,req_variables_copy$Illnesses,req_variables_copy$Hospitalizations)

Barplots were plotted to compare no. of Hospitalizations, Illnesses and Deaths in each year. Maximum hospitalizations were reported in the year 2008. Maximum number of illnesses were reported in the year of 2006 and maximum number of deaths were found in the year 2011.

#2. (a)Bar plot for Year Vs Hospitalizations
p <- ggplot(data =req_variables_copy, aes(x= Year, y = Hospitalizations, xlab="Year", ylab="Hospitalizations")) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity",fill = ('black')) ###theme_classic()
p

#2.(b)Bar plot for Year Vs illnesses
q<-ggplot(data =req_variables_copy, aes(x= Year, y = Illnesses, xlab="Year", ylab="Illnesses")) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity",fill = ('orange'))+
  coord_flip()
q

#2. (c)Bar plot for Year Vs Deaths
r<-ggplot(data =req_variables_copy, aes(x= Year, y = Deaths, xlab="Year", ylab="Deaths")) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity",fill = ('pink'))
r

#filtering out year 2011 values
df1<-req_variables_copy%>%
  select(Year,gspecies,Deaths) %>% 
  filter(Year == 2011, Deaths >0)

Since the maximum number of deaths were reported in the year 2011, filter function was used to filter out the features Year, gspecies, and Deaths in the year 2011 and with deaths greater than zero. A pie chart was created using coord_polar() in the ggplot to find out which genus species resulted in the maximum number of deaths in the year 2011. A similar pie chart was plotted to find out the species causing maximum hospitalizations in the year 2008. A genus species named Listeria Monocytogenes has caused more hospitalizations in 2008 and more deaths in 2011 due to food infection.

#3.(a)Using Pie chart to find the genus species that caused most deaths in the year 2011
df2<-ggplot(df1, aes(x="", y=Deaths, fill=gspecies)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", width=1)+
  coord_polar("y", start=0)+
  theme_void()+ 
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = 'Set1')
print(df2+ggtitle("Species causing Deaths in 2011"))

#filtering out year 2008 values for Hospitalizations
df3<-req_variables_copy%>%
  select(Year,gspecies,Hospitalizations) %>% 
  filter(Year == 2008, Hospitalizations >0)

#3.(b)Using Pie chart to find the genus species that caused most Hospitalizations in the year 2008
df4<-ggplot(df1, aes(x="", y=Hospitalizations, fill=gspecies)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", width=1)+
  coord_polar("y", start=0)+
  theme_void()+ 
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = 'Set1')
print(df2+ggtitle("Species causing Hospitalization in 2008"))

Joint probability is the probability of two different events that occur at the same time. We are calculating this by taking into consideration the genus species and the number of Hospitalizations, which is the frequency. After observing the resultant dataframe, we can see that the maximum number of frequencies has been seen in the genus species of Ciguatoxin,i.e., 172 while Listeria monocytogenes has a frequency of 44.

#Joint Probability:
  
req_variables_df_joint_prob<-req_variables_df %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(prop = n / sum(n))

req_variables_df_joint_prob %>%
  dcast(gspecies~Hospitalizations, value.nar = "n")%>%
  kable(align = "l", format = "pipe",
        table.attr='class="table table-striped table-hover"')

Conditional Probability: Conditional probability is the probability of occurrence of an event X while a secondary event Y is true. Here we are finding the probability of 50-150 hospitalizations that are infected with Listeria monocytogenes.

joint.prob <-req_variables_df_joint_prob %>%
  filter(gspecies == "Escherichia coli, Shiga toxin-producing", Hospitalizations == "5-40") %>%
  .$prop

marg.prob <-req_variables_df_marginal_df %>%
  filter( marginal == "5-40") %>%
  .$marginal

cond.prob <- joint.prob / marg.prob
cond.prob
## numeric(0)

The results show that the genus species, Listeria monocytogenes and Escherichia coli, Shiga toxin-producing are the most infectious after comparing the hospitalizations and deaths in the years 2008 and 2011. We need to further analyze the dataset to understand if there are other features that can influence the number of illnesses, deaths and hospitalizations.
